{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1c3ca928-7d35-4cd6-b044-db0d75efd913","content":"**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compile and run without issues. The syntax is straightforward:\n\n```csharp\nSpan<nint>  a = stackalloc nint[4];\nSpan<nuint> b = stackalloc nuint[3];\n```\n\nOn this 64-bit runtime, `nint.MaxValue` is `9223372036854775807` (same as `long.MaxValue`) and `nuint.MaxValue` is `18446744073709551615` (same as `ulong.MaxValue`), confirming they're 8-byte native-sized integers allocated on the stack.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5802f8e7-4608-4880-a935-76505441dffd","outputTokens":171,"requestId":"FE00:2280B0:13AF4DB:1611CD5:6A066FA6"},"id":"58569066-d0f0-4929-9c68-e30d57e66461","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:58:19.902Z","parentId":"b3508aa4-c098-4639-bacd-b6cd7bb7ace5"}
